item.content:encoded:
When I was first learning jQuery, I remember reading a heap of tutorials and blog posts explaining how to write simple jQuery plugins. These helped me get a handle on the basics, namely building plugins that perform an action on some DOM elements, but they never got to the proper way to write complex plugins. How about an example, eh?

<pre class="prettyprint">
//Zebra stripe some collection of elements by adding an 
//'odd' class to the odd elements
$.fn.zebra = function(classToOdd){
    classToOdd = classToOdd || 'odd';
    this.each(function(i){
        
        if(i % 2)
            $(this).addClass(classToOdd);
        else
            $(this).removeClass(classToOdd);
        
    });
    return this;
};
</pre>

This is a plugin that performs an action (zebra striping) on a collection of elements (think table rows). This plugin carries no state, does not allow the caller to programmatically act on it in the future, and it makes sense in a chain of actions. We'll call this the Basic Style.

I wrote a ton of plugins in the Basic Style. As the complexity of my plugins grew, I noticed this style of plugin architecture was really only well suited to very small plugins. Anything with any substance (say over 300 lines and/or acting on more than one element) just became a steaming black box of code. Much of my beef was that somewhere buried in the plugin was reusable code, functions that could be used to programatically act on the plugin, and functions that should be able to be overridden. There are many publicly available plugins out there written in this way, and they are painful to grok when one needs to fix a bug or extend functionality. 

For the sake of example, I'll pick on "jEditable":http://www.appelsiini.net/download/jquery.jeditable.js , which is a plugin I both like and use. jEditable is written in the Basic Style. While it is well documented, there are 240 lines under the main @this.each()@ call, and almost 100 lines of that chunk are at 7 (seven!) levels of indentation. Ouch. On top of that, what if I want to invoke the editing of some field programatically? I can't without adding something I pass into the options that the plugin understands. What if I don't like the data jEditable sends to the server? Can I override some kind of @saveToServer()@ function without touching the plugin's code? No. Grrr.

Let's start with an example of a plugin in the Basic Style and rewrite it into something more reusable and programmer friendly. Pretend you need to make a plugin that toggles some chunk of markup when you click a link. It might look something like this:

<pre class="prettyprint">
// usage: $('a.some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#mydiv'})
$.fn.toggler = function(options){
    
    var defaults = {
        thingToToggle: null, //can be a selector string or a jquery object
        initiallyOpen: true,
        classWhenOpen: 'open'
    };
    //override our defaults with their options
    options = $.extend({}, defaults, options);
    
    //jqueryify the thing to toggle
    options.thingToToggle = $(options.thingToToggle);
    
    function close(){
        options.thingToToggle.hide();
        options.thingToToggle.removeClass(options.classWhenOpen);
    }
    function open(){
        options.thingToToggle.show();
        options.thingToToggle.addClass(options.classWhenOpen);
    }
    
    options.intiallyOpen ? open() : close();
    
    this.click(function(){
        options.thingToToggle.is(':visible')) ? close() : open();
    });
    return this;
};
</pre> 

Cool. But what if you need to be able to programmatically open and close the @thingToToggle@? With this plugin, you'd need to repeat the @open()@ and @close()@ functions somewhere else. Crappy. Instead, we can make this plugin provide the caller with some API that can access the @open()@ and @close()@ functions. 

How do we give this thing an API? Unfortunately, there are many ways to do it, and none of them really seem to be the 'accepted' way. Every plugin I've used does it differently. Big sadface. :(

First you need to think about how do you want the API to look and be used. Do you want to (or really need to) maintain chainability? An example of potential API's for our toy toggler plugin based on others that I have seen:

<pre class="prettyprint">
//open then close the #my-div element with our little API

// #1
$('a#some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#my-div'});
$.toggler.open($('a#some-link'));
$.toggler.close($('a#some-link'));

// #2; lots of random plugins use this
$('a#some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#my-div'})
    .togglerOpen()
    .togglerClose();

// #3; jQuery UI widgets use this
$('a#some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#my-div'})
    .toggler('open');
    .toggler('close');

// #4; tablesorter mystifyingly binds to events that you can trigger
// with the built-in trigger() function. It looks like this:
$('a#some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#my-div'})
    .trigger('open');
    .trigger('close');

// #5; jquery.validate uses this. 
// The toggler var in this case is an object that only has the open() 
// and close() functions. It is _not_ a jQuery object like in the 
// previous examples.
var toggler = $('a#some-link').toggler({thingToToggle: '#my-div'});
toggler.open();
toggler.close();
</pre>

Beyond implementation, the largest difference between all of these is between examples 1-4 and number 5. Examples 1-4 all maintain chainability by returning the jQuery object they were called on. Example 5 instead returns a meaningful object given the context. 

I am of the opinion that for plugins such as toggler (and a dialog, datatable, chart, etc.)

Also notable is that Examples 1-4 handle being called on a jQuery object with multiple elements a little bit better than Example 5.

